uyGpt-7eScOKFnwNUk7IKw.text: Mr. Snarky introduced me to Konditor and Cook, I introduced him to Wardour Street.  In reality, I hadn't specifically thought of L'Eto, I really just thought about wandering down the street, bakery hopping, drunk on sugar and cake.  I gave him the option to decide and I think the fact that L'Eto has everything on display in the window was a deciding factor.We went in, were greeted and managed to find a seat.  We took turns looking at the goodies in the window.  I wanted to order more than one thing, but I really had to practice some restraint as well.  In the end I had the Ricotta Cheesecake and the Jasmine Passion Fruit Iced Tea.  Mr. Snarky had the Honey Cake (apparently their signature cake) and the Mango Passion Fruit Lassi.  I knew the Ricotta cheesecake would be lighter, but it wasn't nearly as creamy as I was hoping.  And the raisins were surprise... as always.  The surprise was the Honey Cake.  I tried it and I said to Mr. Snarky, "It tastes just like a Graham Cracker!"  He started laughing because it tasted familiar to him, but he couldn't put his finger on it.  Fortunately I had brought him a box of Graham Crackers for him to compare to!  My iced tea was very refreshing, but if you are looking for something sweet, you should try something else.  I figured with a sweet treat, I wouldn't want to go too sweet with my drink.  The Lassi however was lovely.  I have never had Lassi and had it not been made with dairy products, I would've ordered one.I think I would need to go back again to try some of their other items before giving L'Eto anymore stars.  And that is a job I am willing to take!

p_EQZfjLwqmdxAJiJ1hVDw.text: Summary: + Dessert hit and miss + Small cafe + The best thing about this place is the cake display from outside + Free WiFi + Go to Princi or Gails if going for a dessert around here Overall: I went to this small café with great cake display for a tea (and naturally, a cake). Modern and slightly cheap décor reminds me of a breakfast corner of a travel hotel that also multi functions as a bar in the evening. That's not necessarily a bad thing. Somehow the place smelled funny. I think it was kitchen garbage. I'd worked in restaurants before so I'm familiar with the smell. They also have a small salad section like an after thought at the counter. But I wonder if people even notice. I bet most people are lured in to this place by the gorgeous cake display in front. Also, their seating system is a little confusing. I had been here a few times but I still don't know if I'm supposed to secure a seat and then order at the counter or the other way round. Staff are not around to advice either way. Food:My friend and I strategically picked different cakes so we get to taste two. I went for a tiramisu and my friend had ricotta cheesecake. Ricotta cheesecake was good. The thin biscuit base was perfect. Rich and moist. The cake was light but had a funny grainy texture like there are bits of sugar not quite blended in properly to the cake mixture. I wasn't sure about the dried raisins either. The gummy texture and the excessive sweetness of raisins do not add much to the cake. I'm something of a purist when it comes to desserts. So I'd rather have a simple recipe executed perfectly than half-baked flare of random creativity. The way I see it is, there are two ways to use fruits in a dessert situation. One is to add texture and the other is to add sharpness to contrast the sweetness of dessert. Berries are popular for these reasons as they have both juicy texture and pleasant sourness that compliments sweet. I didn't see any of these positive effects from the raisins. Tiramisu was a pure disaster, I'm afraid. Even before I had my first bite, I could see water was oozing out from the bottom layer. As I suspected, this cake was too wet and could hardly maintain its shape. The main cheesecake layers were so runny. The finger biscuit layers in between soaked up so much water that they felt like a sponge in my mouth. (Not that I've ever eaten a sponge before.) I could not finish this horrible water tiramisu. No, hand on. I actually did finish it. But that's just because I'm programmed to finish food in sight. I cursed my mother's teachings as I shoved down this baking disaster down my throat. Next time I see her, I will have to negotiate adding amendments to the age-old rule that allows me to NOT finish food where the quality of food in question is below certain standard. Conclusion: The best thing about this café is the gorgeous cake display. Best to enjoy it from outside.

IQze4FeQKfGMWkhjvu3j7Q.text: We made reservations for a Saturday around 1 pm. It was pretty full, but no line, so I'm not sure that you absolutely need them.It's a pretty tiny place and it has a steady flow of customers. I've only been during the day and I'm not sure if the night is more crowded or less.The servers were nice and answered questions, although one server was a bit too eager with his countless suggestions of what to order. They were also very accommodating with our request to move tables. One of the biggest cons to this place is that most of the chairs are stools, so they don't have backs. I happen to find this quite uncomfortable and when a table opened up that had backs available, we were able to switch.Granny smith pancakes served with fresh berries, vanilla cream, and fruit compote. These were completely delicious and not too sweet at all as can be a huge problem with brunch foods. Small portion, but fantastic.Egg white omelette with spinach & tomatoes, served with sourdough toast. This was the best egg white omelette I've had. Completely not oily, but great flavor. The spinach and tomato was balanced throughout. The bread came toasted and buttered, which I didn't want, so they kindly exchanged it for a piece without any butter. It's also served with a small cute of feta cheese, which I didn't really understand. It was tiny and was sitting in a cup of olive oil. The rest was delicious and I'd highly recommend it if you want something lighter.Flourless chocolate cake - looked rich and dense, but had such a weird flavor. I'm not sure if it was the fact that it was labelled gluten free? Flourless chocolate cakes are naturally gluten free, but usually not labelled as such and don't have this odd taste. This one was specifically labelled gluten free, which may have indicated that they were simply using a different type of flour instead of a no flour. I'm not sure, but there was a molassesy taste that didn't belong. If it hadn't've been for that, it would've been delicious.Would recommend this place for lunch/brunch/snack for sure.

CCeAXDAbDqkaqj8QVPJZfA.text: Finally my friend got to try the infamous honey cake on our second visit last week!  Initially I popped in around 5pm to buy a piece of honey cake to takeaway as it was sure to be sold out if we waited until after dinner.  When I mentioned to the server that the cake is so popular and is always sold out in the evening he kindly offered to save a piece in the fridge so that we could return after dinner.Later on we went back and the verdict on the honey cake which is made up of layers of cake with ground walnuts and cream is that it is light and crumbly and definitely worth the effort to try.  So light that my friend could have eaten another slice but of course there were none left at that hour!  My friend is now blaming me for their addiction to l'eto caffe!I had a halva latte since I could not try the honey cake which contained walnuts, the latte had a pleasant nutty aroma from sunflower and sesame seeds.  I wanted to order one of the custom teas but they had run out of the clear teapots to serve the tea!  So I guess I shall have to return to try the custom tea.

yJn0rJj_Rqf4bIWd6xOAOA.text: I have walked past this place many times, right next to Hummingbird Bakery. Once, my colleague and I wandered in to have a look at their cakes (in our office, the person celebrating their birthday buys the cake - ensuring you are eating something you like) but they were too expensive and there were nothing spectacular on offer.Well, upon someone raving about their honey cakes a few weeks ago, I walked in after work to see only 3 of these honey cakes left at 6:15pm. Duly ordered one to takeaway, noting the eyewatering pricetag of £4.80 (although the cake is a slight generous size) and the gentleman serving was pretty efficient about the whole thing, asking if I needed a plastic fork. No thanks, going to eat it after dinner at home.The most impressive place is really the shop display at the front with all the cakes beautifully laid out. I am not sure it's really worth the price tag though as let's say, I didn't cry out in tears of joy upon tasting this infamous honey cake. It felt like it was too "soft" and not enough crunch in it. jTC8hXnN25iMiIOKfwpByA.text: I love this place and have a terrible time walking by if I can't go in for a cup of tea and something sweet. It's right next door to Hummingbird Bakery and I've never even been into Hummingbird because this place is so much better.L'Eto has a variety of fresh sweet items on display in their huge windows and they're so enticing that I often see people walking by stop to take pictures only to give up and go inside instead.I bring everyone here and always get a mille feuille or fruit tart along with a coffee. Their teas are amazing though and you'll definitely suffer a little envy when you see others order pots of mint or fruit teas which are served in glass pots and are literally muddled mint or fruits steeped in hot water. Visually stunning and very fresh though I still generally stick to a coffee because I'm an addict.They also serve brunch here and I've only had the pleasure of dining here once. I ordered Eggs Florentine and it was perfectly cooked. There is table service but you order at the till and pay first. The staff can get a little overwhelmed on busy days but it's a small place and it's easy to get their attention as a result. The streamlined ordering system makes up for how busy they can get so generally you don't wait very long for drinks and you get your cakes right away.Definitely swing by if you're in Soho and keep an eye on how busy it is. On weekends this place can be absolutely packed!

lmxH8HjjV05HaZ09nKZj4w.text: L'Eto had an adorable ambience. The perfect combination of pop hits through the past decade paired with alternative and indie vibes played through the speakers and most of the walls serve as colorful comment boards. Everyone is welcome in L'Eto. The staff is super friendly, the food is incredible, and dessert is to die for.I got the Italian breakfast -- oyster mushrooms, scrambled eggs, burrata, cherry tomatoes, and sourdough toast. My mouth is watering now just thinking about it. My friend ordered the Californian. It was everything it was advertised to be and very good, but unmemorable. It consisted of tortilla chips, fried eggs, queso fresco, guacamole, and pico served over a tortilla. Our food came out quickly, and the service was great. We finished lunch off with dessert. For me, a chocolate fudge cake. For her, the pistachio rose cake. Mine was what I expected -- thick, dense, fudge. Hers was beyond expectation. It was absolutely incredible. Light, fluffy flavors exploded in every bite. We will definitely be going back! Might try something new on the entree menu, but we need more of that cake.

Unfortunately, a very dismal experience and taste. Perhaps service and cleanliness has nosedived since my last visit...

SS2peLfQ6rDFMLC8pD8eNQ.text: L'Eto Caffe is a beautiful, casual dining spot where I experienced the most modern elegant food during my entire stay in London.The pastry explosion in the front window did help to draw me in, but I really focused on the breakfast menu during my visit.The options did not excite me at first, but I persisted and took a chance on the scrambled eggs with feta, tomatoes, and avocado tartine.  My lord it was a revelation!  I added Bacon, but in hindsight I could have skipped it.The eggs were perfectly soft scrambled, the tartine was incredibly delicious toast that was drizzled with a chili oil, covered with ripe avocado and a sprinkle of toasted sunflower seeds.  There was a little disc of feta in olive oil and herbs on the side, a condiment I suppose.  And then a little salad of quartered cherry tomatoes in a little dish on the plate.A side of fresh orange juice was perfectly done, other juice combos are available.If you're looking for the full English breakfast experience, go elsewhere.  If you want something amazing, give it a try!

B-_Y7bF5F-AhnbTRdk0skQ.text: This place serves breakfast until 5 pm. What's not to like?? I got the Nutella crepes and a pot of hot cocoa. The cocoa was ultra rich delicious, and the crepes too were amazing. My dad got a cappuccino, and it was so beautiful he didn't want to drink it! He said it was the best cappuccino he ever had, too! He also said that his soft - boiled eggs were over cooked... but let's not ruin the moment. The cakes in the window looked crazily amazing (crazemazing????), and everyone seemed to be enjoying their food. Some of the coffees even came as a see-through cup with milk in an erlenmeyer flask with the espresso in a tiny beaker so you could make your own concourse. GENIUS!!! This place is amazing and whoever says otherwise doesn't know what they're talking about!

dUHVTtx-t2AYGgYvxelFlg.text: A small pastries cafe in SOHO. Lots of interesting desserts. If you are dining anywhere nearby, it is probably a good idea to skip the dessert and visit this place instead. You'll get a lot more options and cost a lot less. The chocolate hazelnut cake is like a very light Nutella mouse with a thin crispy crust at the bottom. The green tea lychee cheese cake has a very pronounced lychee flavor albeit it tasted a little artificial after a while. The Caribbean carrot cake seemed a little dryer than what I'm used to at first; but it definitely grew on me later. The creamy filling and the mango jam on top really made on favorite of the three. I wish I had the stomach to try some others; I'll have to wait until my next visit.

P82NI1kLBShVz1k_qi7RiA.text: Super cute bakery with pretty and delicious desserts! I came here on a Sunday around 6pm and there was a small line for seating but no line for ordering to go. I ordered the rose and lychee cake, the almond and lemon cake and the caramel cake. The rose/lychee and the almond/lemon cake were so good and moist! Usually pretty desserts are much less tasty, but these two cakes had me pleasantly surprised! I would order these two over and over again! The caramel cake had a weird texture (almost like baklava) and the flavor wasn't that great. They have a large selection of interesting flavored desserts from pies to cakes to brownies and soufflés! The shop itself is also very cute and whimsical! The three desserts I ordered was a total of about 19 pounds, so it is a bit pricey but I expected that just by looking at the shop.

d-4nQEY7wykNcNFfMUNt_g.text: L'eto is honestly one of the best places to go for cake. You can't not try their signature honey cake plus their tea and coffee selection is quite unique. But he warned there are times when it is full so you will wait anywhere from 5-20 minutes. a4m16AHM6ys7PJhYHXqFuQ.text: Best brunch we had in a while! 100% recommending it to everyone! Amazing Egg Benedict and delicious pancakes! Service is great and waiters are very friendly (we had Anthony as our server and was great).Amazing decor too!

U0K3nL3NvgCkQPsgjqP1eQ.text: We came here with my friends for a Sunday brunchThe place itself it's pretty small  but comfy. The atmosphere is nice and the decoration is simple but great. The music was Christmas songs and other nice modern ones (Adele for example...)The staff was really nice and friendly. However, the service was REALLY slow which made me a bit disappointed. We were three people: two of us were served and the last one has to wait more than 15 min to be served (after we asked a waitress for it). I understand than all the orders can't arrive at the same time but more 15 minutes difference it's a lot...Most important: the food! Everything was really tempting on the menu! I chosed the poached eggs with an almond milk cappucino and a rose and lychee cake on the side. l'Eto Caffe has a HUGE cakes choice and they all look good! (I will come to try more for sure...)I recommend this place for a nice brunch or a small tea time break in the afternoon. Nice place, nice food and nice people. A good combo :)

f5J6Y01PaFXu_IBLYdInlg.text: We came here for brunch. The food was bland on texture and taste. I'd describe the Arabic as a plate of mush. Petty, given the cost of our brunch. Atmosphere and service did not make up for bad food

xN0LAxM2MjrK0RlVHUf2CQ.text: I was walking to Princi when L'eto Caffe's window display of tempting desserts caught my eye. I then looked up and admired their interior: dark wood and black with silver accents, brightly lit and welcoming. I decided to stick with the plan and go to Princi anyway, but the lack of seating quickly convinced me to go back and give L'eto Caffe' a try. We got a burata salad, burata cheese with tomatoes and rocket, and polenta (in pie form) with sundried tomatoes. Both needed seasoning quite badly, so I asked for salt and pepper grinders. The first salt grinder didn't work that well, and I ended up switching and wrestling with two others until I found one that worked. Coffee looked gorgeous in Bodum Pavina double-walled glasses, but was mediocre and disappointing. Since they just opened, I would assume that they are still working out their kinks, but until then, I'll be going to Princi.

r-IXOECAIlUYBtS0TftwVg.text: I have started dropping in to Caffe L'Eto on a regular basis because everything they serve is really good quality and beautifully presented. They put a lot of care and attention into everything they do - and that is rare in London and should be supported. They also serve the best green tea I have ever tasted.

0MtXwXDQuw0AwVF6y47dYg.text: I'd been in before to grab some takeout, and been hugely impressed by the passionfruit meringue and birdberry cake. This time I sat down with a honey cake and the red berry and mint tea, and it was just amazing. The cake was, quite simply, perfect, and the tea was incredibly expensive but delicious. I'd go back in a heartbeat.

0-N4F7SclV97iA45HiOonA.text: Seating is always a problem at our beloved Princi, so my flattie and I were very glad to discover this new little cafe just two steps away. We didn't have a go with any savoury dishes, but only had two of the sweet treats of the window: the meringue tart and the brownie. The second was a very moist and chocolatey version, well-executed and overall very satisfactory. Now the tart... I don't think I have ever tasted quite anything like it. Perhaps inspired by a Sicilian cassata, it encrusted a wildly tangy mix of red berries in perfect pastry (between shortcrust and puff!..) and sweet meringue. I still don't know if I liked it really, but it's great to have a new place around that dares to offer new tastes. On the drinks front, the relatively overpriced jasmine green tea was great, flattie says, and my bottled pink lemonade was more or less what I expected. We'll definitely be there again, as it's a refreshing alternative to the very crowded atmosphere of Princi, if one doesn't feel like it!
